== Visualizing Results

When the training is complete, you will obtain a `W` and a `b`, allowing us to visually present the dataset and the fitted results through charts.

While writing this, I trained a result using the above code:

// Image: Training Results (https://ws1.sinaimg.cn/large/006tKfTcly1fh0l0w2j86j30l3011dfu.jpg)

We can directly write it into the code as:

```python
w = [0.12888144, 0.12310864]
b = -15.47322273
```

Next, we will first represent the dataset on the chart (x1 on the horizontal axis, x2 on the vertical axis):

```python
x1 = train_data[:, 0]
x2 = train_data[:, 1]
y = train_data[:, -1:]

for x1p, x2p, yp in zip(x1, x2, y):
    if yp == 0:
        plt.scatter(x1p, x2p, marker='x', c='r')
    else:
        plt.scatter(x1p, x2p, marker='o', c='g')
```

Here, we use `red x` to represent `not admitted` and `green o` to represent `admitted`.

Next, we will represent the decision boundary obtained from training `XW + b = 0` on the chart:

```python
# Get the line based on parameters
x = np.linspace(20, 100, 10)
y = []
for i in x:
    y.append((i \* -w[1] - b) / w[0])

plt.plot(x, y)
plt.show()
```

At this point, if your code is correct, running it again will yield the following result:

// Image: Fitting Results (https://ws2.sinaimg.cn/large/006tKfTcly1fh0l1ktu4kj30m80iwmyq.jpg)

As we can see, the parameters obtained from training draw a line that effectively separates the two different data samples.

